consent:
Thank you for participating! 

 

This project is designed to study the way people judge whether certain situations are right or wrong. You will to have rate a series of events on three different scales. The entire study should take approximately 25 minutes.
Key Information 


Your participation is entirely voluntary and you may withdraw at any point. However, you must answer all questions, perform all tasks, and proceed to the final screen of the study in order to receive a link for your payment. For successful participation in the study, you will receive $2.71, paid by transfer to your Prolific account. 

 

We will adhere, at all times, to strict standards of confidentiality. Information obtained through your participation will be accessible only by the research team. Your name will not be attached to your data in any way. Although collected data may be made public or used for future research purposes, your identity will always remain confidential. 

 

You must be in the United States to qualify to participate in this study. If you are not, you will be directed to the end of the survey after this page. Further, in accordance with Prolific policies, we may reject your work if the task was not completed correctly or the instructions were not followed.



This is a study about moral transgressions and, therefore, the vignettes that you will have to evaluate might contain graphic and/or violent language (e.g. references to murder or sexual violence). If this is in any way distressing, please feel free to abstain from participation.



If you have questions, you may contact Duke Researchers at nr120@duke.edu. If you have any questions about your rights as a research participant, please contact the Duke University Human Subjects Protection Committee at campusIRB@duke.edu. 



By clicking “I agree to participate” you indicate that you understand the study description above, that you understand the qualifications to participate in this study, that you will follow instructions in the study, and that you agree to participate. You may save and/or print this form if you want to.
welcome:
Welcome and thank you for deciding to take part in the present study! Before you begin, please read the following instructions carefully:

 

Most of our everyday interactions are normal and mundane and go by unnoticed. However, events that involve moral transgressions often stick out; they seem more or less harmful, more or less unexpected.


In the current task, we will present you some scenarios and will ask you to tell us how immoral, unexpected, and harmful you think they are. Throughout the questionnaire, you will also be shown some active participation checks. These look just like the other questions, except that you will be told exactly what option to choose. They will help us ensure you are completing the task carefully. 

 

Please remember to read all questions and instructions carefully so that you are sure to respond to all participation checks correctly. Failing to do so will result in a loss of payment. If you are completing the survey on your cellphone, make sure to turn your device sideways (to landscape mode) so that all questions are displayed properly.

 

A final word of warning before we begin: the following vignettes might contain strong and graphic language. If you would rather not be exposed to such language, please feel free to abstain from participation. Thank you!

db:
Thank you for your participation. We would like to tell you about the purpose of the study you've just completed.
As stated in the beginning of the survey, this study was designed to study how people interpret moral transgressions. More specifically, the goal of the project is to understand how the meanings we attach to the people involved in situations influence the extent to which we perceive those events as immoral. We are less surprised when certain types of people commit immoral acts, and we are less surprised when certain types of people are the victims of such actions.
The scenarios used in this study contain different types of identities as well as different kinds of moral transgressions. This study is interested in how different combinations of these elements might affect how we make moral judgements. Your participation in this study will help researchers better understand how the structure of certain events might lead us to more readily identify moral wrongdoing.
Thank you again for your time and participation. If you have any questions regarding this study, please contact us by email at nr120@duke.edu.
